@NODE Tool "Tool Types"

@{b}Tool Types:@{ub}
-----------

    FONTNAME=topaz
    FONTSIZE=8

These 2 tool types allow you to use any reasonably sized font for your
menus, message display and window title in VGA mode.  If the program is
unable to find this font then it will use topaz 8 as the default.


    GUIFONTNAME=topaz
    GUIFONTSIZE=8
    
This font will be used in the Options window, the Color adjustment window
as well as in the statistics window.  The GUI font has to be proportional
in order for the statistics page to be properly formatted.  The included
gammon font works quite well at 800x600 or 1024x768.


------------------------------------------------------------------------
If there are any problems with option windows not opening up then it is
likely because the GUI font you are trying to use is too BIG.  Using a 
24 point font on a 640x200 NTSC screeen is not going to work properly.   
------------------------------------------------------------------------



    NAME=

Use the above so you won't be called Buddy anymore.  My dog appreciates
it.  Name lengths can now be as long as 19 characters including spaces.


    NUMBERS
    
This will number the points on the board from 1 to 24.   


    SCREEN=
   
This tool type will bypass the initial screen mode requester window.
Simply use any 8 digit hexidecimal screen mode code.  After you have
found a screen mode that you like you can run the included program  
ScreenTool  to find the appropriate code. 

SCREEN=50041000  will automatically open up an 8 bit - 800x600 UAE 
SVGA screen.  SCREEN=29000  or  SCREEN=00029000 will open up the 
default PAL High Res screen with a resolution of 640x256.


    WORKBENCH
    
If 8 digit hexidecimal screen mode codes are hurting your brain then
simply use the WORKBENCH tool type.  ProGammon will now try and use
a screen mode the same as what you are presently using for your main
Workbench screen.  Very simple.    


    CUBE
    
This is the start of a doubling cube.  So far, it only doubles the stakes
of the game when both players roll the same thing on the opening roll.
A mouse click in the upper right hand corner will show you the present
status of the cube when this option is activated.

    

    CPU=
    MAN=
    
These two tool types will allow you to set the board up any way you wish.
The format for version 2.9 has changed and is more flexible.

Here's how it works:

    CPU=02000000000050000305
    MAN=0000005030000500000000002
    
Those 2 lines entered as tool types would allow you to set the board
up in the traditional manner.  The first digit corresponds to the number
of stones on the bar.  The next 24 positions on the board correspond
to the next 24 digits after the first zero.

The board is numbered from 1 to 24.  See  @{" The Basics " LINK Basic}.  The first line 
translates as follows.  The CPU has 0 stones on the bar, 2 stones on the
1 point, 5 stones on the 12 point, 3 on the 17 point and 5 more on the 
19 point.

Both tool types are not required.  You can use either, neither or both.

The letters A through F are also available to place between 10 and 15
stones on any point.

Another example: if you wanted to set the board up so that the game starts
with 15 stones on the bar for the Amiga and 10 stones on the bar for you
then use the following:

    CPU=F
    MAN=A


The first digit represents the bar so CPU=F will place 15 stones on the
bar and MAN=A places 10 stones on the bar for you.  There is nothing
else after the F or the A so nothing else will be placed on the board.


    NODICETABLE
    
This program normally rolls the dice 1024 times and then saves the
results in a big look up table.  If you would like to have the dice rolled
in real time then use the above tool type to prevent the dice table from
being created.


    DOUBLETEST
    
Some people complain that there are either too many or not enough doubles
rolled in a game.  The above tool type will keep track of how many
doubles are rolled each game and then a small table will be created in a
file in your RAM: directory called  doubles.txt.  There will most likely
be 8 doubles rolled during a game but there may be games in which no 
doubles are rolled for either player.  There may be other games where 
a total of more than 25 doubles occur.  These events though are extremely 
rare.
  
There is a 95% probability that between 4 and 15 doubles will occur during
a traditional game of backgammon.  I have included a sample  doubles.txt  
file that was output after a set of 100000 games showing the outcomes.  


    REGISTER=
    
This tool type is used to register the program.  You can register this
program by sending me an e-mail and telling me what you think.  This will
remove the About nag requester when the program first starts and motivate
me to add another feature or two someday like a real doubling cube.    

@ENDNODE

@NODE Auto "Auto Mode"

@{b}Auto Mode:@{ub}
----------

Clicking the mouse in the lower right portion of the board will start
automatic game play.  The center portion of the bar will change colors
while you're in Auto Mode.  The Amiga now takes over rolling the dice
and making moves for both players.

Basically, this turns the program into Amiga vs Amiga game play.

Let the computer play overnight and then you can check the  Stats  screen
to see if the dice really are random.  Also check for wins/gammons etc.

Novice players may learn a thing or two by watching the game play against
itself.

A single click of the mouse anywhere should return control to the user.

This feature is handy when you are way ahead or behind in a game and the 
outcome is obvious.  Put the program into Auto Mode and then sit back 
while the Amiga completes the game for you.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Open "Opening Moves"

@{b}Opening Moves:@{ub}
--------------

There are 15 unique opening moves possible in the game of backgammon.
For thousands of years there has been the ongoing debate of what is the
best way to play each one.

I did some extensive Amiga vs Amiga testing to try and compare some of
the moves that are recommended in various backgammon texts.

In real backgammon situations where you need a gammon to win a multi-
point match then it's possible that some opening moves with a poor 
overall winning percentage might actually be preferred because they have 
a better gammon winning percentage.  A doubling cube could also change
these results significantly.

I am not here to claim that the moves found are the ultimate opening 
moves.  If the level that PG plays at is not strong enough then these 
results may be meaningless.  If your style of game play is significantly
different than how ProGammon plays then your opening moves are also
likely going to be different.

The following opening moves are recommended when playing single point 
games against ProGammon and make a good starting point for most players.

Version 2.9 Update:  This program plays more of a running game compared
to previous versions.  Some of the opening moves that ProGammon uses
have changed based on the following tests.  Previous test results are 
listed in the right hand column for comparison.  

The initial results were based on 20,000 game sets and to improve 
accuracy I used sets of 40,000 games.  There is a 95% probability that
these results are accurate to within plus or minus ( +/- 0.005 ).
Previously, using 20,000 game sets, there was a 95% probability that
the results were accurate to witin plus or minus ( +/- 0.007 ).

When two moves are within 0.010 of each other after 40 000 games then 
either one could come out on top during a larger set of games and 
should be considered equal.  

After 2 million games of Amiga vs Amiga, here are the results:


ROLL     YOUR MOVE         RESULTS        OLD

2-1     13/11, 24/23  PM    0.503        0.495
        24/22, 24/23        0.494        -----
        24/21               0.493        0.500
