@NODE Close "Closing Moves"

@{b}Closing Moves:@{ub}
--------------

Everyone studies and debates the opening moves in backgammon but what
about the closing moves.  I am referring to positioning your final two
stones to maximize the probability that you will get both of them off
with your next roll and win the game.

Many inexperienced players can make a mistake here and end up losing
a game that they should have and could have won.

Example time.  Suppose you have two stones left, 1 on your 6 point and
the other one on your 4 point.  Now suppose you roll a ( 1, 2 ).  You
can't bear anything off with this roll but how should you position
yourself to better your chances of winning with your next roll?

If you moved the stone from your 4 point to your 1 point then you would
be left with stones on the 1 and the 6.  You could also choose to move
the stone from the 6 point down to the 3 point leaving you with stones
on the 3 and the 4 point.  The last possibility would be to move the
6 stone to the 5 point and to move the stone from the 4 point to the
2 point.  


STONES LEFT    WINNING MOVES    PERCENTAGE
    1-1              36           100.0%
    1-2              36           100.0%
    1-3              34            94.4%
    1-4              29            80.6%
    1-5              23            63.9%
    1-6              15            41.7%
    2-2              26            72.2%
