When you roll a set of dice there are 36 different possiblities.  In the
chart above 1-1 means you have two stones left and they are both on the
1 point.  With your next roll of the dice there are 36 of a possible 36
rolls that will win the game for you.

In my example you are left with the choice of leaving your stones on 
either the 1 and the 6, the 2 and the 5 or the 3 and the 4 point.

1-6 = 0.417
3-4 = 0.472
2-5 = 0.528


It is obvious from the above that leaving your stones on the 2 and the 5
is the best move.  Correctly playing your closing move can be far more 
rewarding to your winning percentage than correctly playing your opening 
move.  Unfortunately, games are often times decided before this stage.
Version 2.9 of ProGammon does a better job setting up for the close.


If you can't memorize the above table then simply remember to space out 
your last two stones by 2 or 3 positions and avoid stacking them on the 
same point.

