@NODE Pip "The Pip Count"

@{b}Counting Pips:@{ub}
--------------

Backgammon strategy depends on whether you're ahead or behind in the race
home.  It's not smart to make overly risky moves when you are way ahead 
but you better start making some aggresive moves if you've fallen behind.

One way to determine if you are ahead or behind is called counting pips
or points.  At the start of a normal game of backgammon, each player will
have to roll 167 points to bring all their stones home and bear them off.


    Stones      Point       Pips
       2    x     24    =    48
       5    x     13    =    65
       3    x      8    =    24
       5    x      6    =    30
                           ----
                            167
                            
                            
At any time during the game you can go through the board and do this
calculation.  If the Amiga's pip count is 120 and yours is only 90 then
you are leading the race by 30 points.  A positive difference means that
you are leading and a negative difference means that you are behind.

The Amiga will calculate the pip count difference and display it at the
lower left part of the screen.  During game play, simply click the mouse
once on the Amiga dice to display this information.


My Method:
----------

Most backgammon books use the above method for counting pips but I found
that the number returned isn't always meaningful, especially when bearing
off has begun.

For example, who's winning if you have 12 stones left on your 1 point and 
the Amiga has 2 stones left on its 6 point (point 19 on the board).  Both 
players have a pip count of 12 points but it is obvious that the Amiga is
going to win most of the time.  Even if you get to roll first, the Amiga
will win 99.9% of the time so a net pip of 0, which suggests that the game
is even, is completely misleading.


RollPip:
--------

I decided to come up with a slightly more complex calculation that takes
the above situation into account.  My pip count is called the RollPip or
Rolls for short.

It measures how many rolls of the dice are required for each player to
bear all their stones off and then displays the difference.  Once again,
a positive number means that you are leading and a negative number means
that you are behind.

Click on the Amiga dice to get this number displayed in the lower left
part of the window.  A display of  Rolls = 3.0  means that the Amiga will
need approximately 3 extra rolls of the dice to get back in the race.  
A large double or knocking one of your stones off to the bar will even 
things up in a hurry. 

If  Rolls = 0.0  is displayed then the Amiga has determined that the 
race is about dead even.  If this is displayed before you make your move 
then you are probably slightly ahead since you have control of the dice.
A poor roll like (1,2) means that you'll likely be behind after your turn
is complete whereas an above average roll like double sixes (6,6) will 
definitely put you clearly ahead in the race.

In the above example, the Pip is 0 but Rolls = -3.7. This suggests that
you don't have a snowballs chance in hell of winning the game which was
proven correct.


Conclusion:
-----------

Both of these methods of counting pips are only simple approximations of
who is winning the game.  They don't take into account good positions like
having some stones trapped behind a prime of 6 or having one of your
opponents stones on the bar while you have a closed inner board.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Dice "Testing the Dice"

@{b}The Dice:@{ub}
---------

The dice are generated using the SAS/C random number generating function
called drand48().  I have done a 1001 tests and rolled these dice a 100
million times and I am thoroughly convinced that the numbers returned by 
this function are 100% random.  There is no difference whatsoever between 
the randomness of the dice in ProGammon compared to a real pair of dice 
rolled by the typical user. 

Most computer backgammon players are very suspicious of the dice, never 
when they win but always when they lose!  The dice are now pre-rolled
before the first game.  There are enough pre-determined dice rolls for 
approximately 20 complete games.  No program can predict what moves you
are going to make so it is absolutely impossible to arrange the dice file
to the advantage/disadvantage of either player.
       
If the Amiga rolls double 6's for it's last roll and wins it is because 
it got damn lucky!

You can now see exactly what dice rolls are coming up.  At the start of a
game when it says,  Click Mouse To Roll  , just click the mouse in the 
lower left corner of the board.  This will create a file called  dice.txt  
in your  RAM:  directory.  This file contains what the dice are going to 
roll for the next, approximately, 20 games.  Any statistical analysis on 
this file will prove to you the 100% randomness of the dice.  

No more suspicious, surprise, miracle rolls for the Amiga!


Every roll of the dice is also kept track of in the  gammon.prefs  file 
after you select  Quit  in the menus or close the game screen.  

During the game, you can select  Stats  in the menus to see the averages 
for the games that you are presently playing.  By clicking on the right 
portion of the statistics screen you can also examine the stats saved in 
the  gammon.prefs  file.


Is there any way now that ProGammon can cheat?  Sure.  The program could
cheat by looking ahead in the dice file.  It's obvious that the Amiga
could make a risky move if it knew for sure that your next roll would
not give you the opportunity to make contact.  It could also avoid risky
moves if it determined that your next roll would make contact.

Does it cheat like this?  Certainly not, and I can prove it!

After the first roll, every move is predictable and repeatable.  What 
this means is that if the board is set up in a certain way and a certain
number shows up on the dice then it is always going to make the exact
same move regardless of what's in the dice file.

If you witness a very suspicious looking move during game play then stop
and do the following.

There are now @{" Options " LINK Options} and @{" Tool Types " LINK Tool} available for you to recreate 
the exact same situation.  Once you have recreated the position of the 
stones on the board, you can then use the  User Dice  option to enter in 
what the dice roll was.  Turn off the  Random Moves  option and the Amiga 
should now proceed to make the identical move to what it made during game 
play.

This proves that the dice file is not being used in any way to gain an 
advantage over you.  It would have made that exact same move anyhow.


I have done everything I can think of to prove that ProGammon does not 
cheat.  I really have nothing to gain by writing such a program.

If you don't trust ProGammon rolling the dice this way then you can use
the tool type  NODICETABLE  and the dice will be rolled in real time as
they are needed.  If you don't trust the internal random number generator
then you can always use your own dice with this program by selecting the
User Dice option.

If you have any other "it cheats" theories then let me know and I will
be happy to prove to you otherwise.  My butt is covered!


Remember, winning against this game is easy.  Don't use "bad dice" as an 
excuse for playing a "bad game"! 

