What this all means is don't get too excited when you have a bad night
playing Yahoo! backgammon.  I have found that most highly ranked players, 
who have earned their rankings honestly by playing against other highly 
ranked players, are not winning more than 55% of the games they play.

In fact, I found one player with a ranking of over 3500 points yet his 
winning percentage was only 0.504.  The Yahoo ranking system is mostly 
based on the number of games completed.  If you play 10,000+ games and 
you win half of them then you can have a top ranking at Yahoo too.


I decided to create a somewhat similar rating system in ProGammon.  Win 
some games and your rating will go up, lose some and it will go down.  
After you have completed 100 games you will be able to see how you are
doing by clicking on the Amiga's dice a couple of times.

A long term 2000 point ProGammon player should be competitive with most 
any player they meet at Yahoo! or anywhere else.

Unlike Yahoo, the ProGammon rating number should become more meaningful
as you play more and more games.  The Yahoo number seems to become 
completely meaningless after playing thousands of games.

