@NODE Advanced "Advanced Section"

@{b}Backgammon Simulations:@{ub}
-----------------------

During a game of backgammon you often times get to a stage when you have
to make a decision about whether to run home, make a hit, hold on to a 
key point or whatever.

One way to compare 2 moves is to write down what the board would look
like after each move.  Now, let the computer play against itself a few
thousand times for each version.  Compare the resulting 2 different
winning percentages and you might get some more insight into what the
best move to make is.

You can also do this sort of testing on moves recommended by the experts.
You will find that PG still has plenty of room for improvement!

In order to be able to do this kind of testing then you are going to 
need the following tools:


    CPU=
    MAN=
    
These two tool types will allow you to set the board up anyway you wish.


    [ Amiga Starts ]
    [ You Start ]
    
In the above situation you would be using the  [ Amiga Starts ]  option
because you just finished your turn and the Amiga will be rolling the 
dice next.    


    [ Random Moves ]
    
To make sure that your tests are consistent, you should eliminate the
random opening moves by turning off the above  Option.    


    TEST
    TEST=1000
    
This tool type turns off the majority of the graphics, sets the speed at
15 and automatically starts playing against itself.  This greatly 
increases the number of games/hour that the Amiga can complete.  The 
more games played, the more meaningful your results will be.  My A1200
with a 28mhz 68030 is good for about 1900 games/hour.  My Dell 866 mHz
Pentium III laptop running WinUAE can finish about 40,000 games per hour
and an AMD XP-2400+ will play over 100,000 games per hour.

You can use the TEST tool type to play an infinite number of games or 
you can use it with a condition like TEST=1000 to play exactly 1000 games.

Remember to make sure that the boards being compared are set up properly
before doing any long term testing.

The stats can be examined at any time during testing and then you can 
continue on by resuming Auto Mode.

After 40,000 games there is a 95% probability that the results will be
accurate to within plus or minus 0.005.  Two equal players should have
winning averages somewhere between 0.495 and 0.505.

Give me access to a supercomputer and I'll give you a better backgammon 
algorithm!

